the best way to prevent a resurgence of power 
by the khmer rouge in cambodia is to hold free elections and let 
the cambodian people reject the faction the state department said 
friday 
but the departments statement did not rule out a role in an 
interim coalition government for the khmer rouge under whose 
former rule international human rights groups estimate onefourth 
of cambodias 8 million people died from famine or execution 
fear of a return to power by the khmer rouge the strongest of 
three insurgent groups in a cambodian resistance coalition led by 
usbacked prince norodom sihanouk has been a major stumbling 
block to a negotiated settlement with the vietnameseinstalled 
government 
sihanouk is scheduled to meet with hun sen the vietnambacked 
cambodian leader on may 2 in jakarta indonesia 
the state department comments followed vietnams announcement 
this week that it would pull its remaining troops out of cambodia 
by the end of september ending an 11year occupation that ousted 
the communist khmer rouge from power 
the united states totally opposes a return to dominance by the 
khmer rouge the statement said 
the united states envisions an arrangement in cambodia in which 
an interim coalition government is headed by sihanouk the 
logical leader of such an arrangement the statement said 
whether the khmer rouge minus pol pot and the other 
discredited khmer rouge leaders who clearly must be excluded are 
permitted to participate in such an interim arrangement is 
something the cambodian factions themselves will have to decide 
the department said 
we are convinced that in free and fair elections for a 
permanent government the cambodian people would reject the khmer 
rouge it said 
any future arrangements for a return to democracy in cambodia 
would also have to include effective guarantees to prevent 
power from falling into the hands of the khmer rouge the 
department said 
us officials say such safeguards would include an 
international force to monitor the vietnamese pullout a halt to 
outside supply of arms to the cambodian factions and improved 
international access to the khmer rouge camps along the 
thaicambodian border 
international human rights groups and us officials have 
accused the faction of committing atrocities against prisoners 
taken to those camps 
the us view has concerned some asian countries who reject any 
role for the khmer rouge even an interim one but us officials 
say the group is a fact of life and has too much power in the 
resistance coalition to be ignored 
china announced this week that it would continue arming the 
khmer rouge until vietnam makes good on its promise to pull out its 
troops estimated to number 50000 to 70000 
meanwhile rep stephen j solarz dny chairman of the house 
foreign affairs subcommittee on asia called friday for the bush 
administration to send military aid to the forces backing sihanouk 
and one of his allies son sann 
the united states should do everything it can to support the 
resistance against the khmer rouge said solarz who just returned 
from discussions in china and thailand on the situation in cambodia 
he proposed that the united nations establish an interim 
government in cambodia to set up a political settlement through 
elections 
