<TEXT>
the bush administration wants house lawmakers 
to begin slicing chunks of money off a fiscal 1989 spending bill 
that has more than doubled in size in recent days 
figures gathered friday showed that after a week of work by the 
subcommittees of the house appropriations committee a measure 
proposed by president bush for 22 billion in new spending this 
year has grown to 46 billion 
richard darman director of the white house office of management 
and budget sent a letter thursday to rep silvio conte rmass 
ranking republican on the appropriations panel warning the 
lawmakers that because of the added expenditures he would urge 
bush to veto the bill 
darman noted that under a 1987 budget summit agreement between 
thenpresident reagan and congressional leaders additional 
spending for this year could be allowed only in case of a dire 
emergency 
in action taken this week we believe several of the house 
appropriations subcommittees have adopted items that are a clear 
violation of the summit agreement darman wrote 
conte said in an interview that he agreed that the extra 
spending should not be on the bill 
theyre not going to get anywhere with this he said 
referring to house democrats who are pushing the more generous 
version of the spending measure 
the new spending appended by the lawmakers includes 726 million 
for antidrug efforts including money for prisons police officers 
and prevention programs 256 million to pay reparations to 
japaneseamericans interned during world war ii and 350 million 
on top of a 250 million request by bush to pay the costs of 
fighting last years western forest fires 
the subcommittees also ignored a 11 percent acrosstheboard 
slash that bush had proposed in many domestic programs 
that cut would have saved 829 million but was attacked by 
critics for deriving onethird of its savings from programs for the 
poor 
the deficit for fiscal 1989 which ends sept 30 was recently 
projected by omb at 1702 billion excluding this bill the budget 
resolution passed by congress last spring called for a 1989 deficit 
of 142 billion for technical reasons the total for new spending 
in a bill frequently differs from the impact the measure will have 
on the governments red ink 
among other expenditures added to the bill by the subcommittees 
were 96 million for the customs service and other justice 
department law enforcement agencies plus 36 million for 
drugtesting and other antidrug efforts by the federal aviation 
administration 
in addition the lawmakers inserted 35 million for the faa to 
hire more security officers safety inspectors and air traffic 
controllers 35 million for the prosecution of savings and loan 
fraud cases and 32 million for improvements in weather 
forecasting equipment and for other national weather service 
expenses 
bushs bill had included 892 million for the guaranteed student 
loan program for college students 850 million for costofliving 
increases in veterans benefits and other department of veterans 
affairs programs 423 million for foster care and adoption 
programs 100 million for the costs of increased immigration from 
the soviet union southeast asia and africa and 55 million for 
the governments uranium program 
the full appropriations committee is expected to consider the 
bill no earlier than the week of april 18 the senate has yet to 
work on the measure 
</TEXT>
