<TEXT>
laws approved by parliament this week have 
ushered in a new era of competitive elections in poland that will 
break the communist partys long monopoly on power 
the laws also created a new legislative chamber that will be the 
east blocs first such democratically elected body 
polish lawmakers passed their historic reforms friday in a quick 
series of votes as amendments to the constitution they created a 
presidency a freely elected senate and new electoral laws 
a solidarity committee created by leader lech walesa plans to 
meet today to discuss potential opposition candidates 
the constitutional amendments follow major political reforms in 
the soviet union which last month held its first contested 
elections in seven decades of communist rule however only 
candidates approved by officially sanctioned groups were allowed to 
run in the soviet races 
the bills stem from an agreement wednesday in an 
oppositiongovernment committee on political reform the group 
formed part of twomonth talks between the solidarityled 
opposition and communist authorities 
the opposition agreed to participate in the sejm or parliament 
in exchange for restoration of the legal status of the independent 
trade union solidarity the union was banned after authorities 
imposed martial law in december 1981 
the amendments call for creating a 100member senate to be 
freely elected in june 
the senates primary function will be to act as a control on the 
sejm especially in the field of human rights as well as 
socioeconomic life wednesdays agreement said 
the current 460member sejm will remain in place as the 
supreme authority of legislative power however 35 percent of 
its seats will now be open to candidates independent of the polish 
united workers communist party 
the party and its allies will occupy the other 65 percent 
making the communists a minority party that must work with 
coalition partners to create a voting majority 
those allies the democratic party and the united peasant party 
thus expect to gain more independence and power the arrangement 
could produce some lively results in now placid chamber 
anyone who collects 3000 signatures can run for the senate or 
for the independent sejm seats 
previously only candidates approved by election commissions 
formed by the communist party and its allies could be placed on the 
ballot 
the election law also guarantees the opposition access to 
statecontrolled media and the chance to publish a newspaper during 
the campaign 
the constitutiomal amendments also create a post of president 
which existed in poland before world war ii 
while the legislative changes are meant to enhance democracy 
the sixyear presidency is a partyinspired brake to ensure that 
the party retains control for the immediate future 
the presidents term of office will last six years he can 
refuse to sign a bill into law however the sejm can overrule a 
presidential veto with a twothirds vote 
the sejm and senate jointly elect the president who is expected 
to be polish leader gen wojciech jaruzelski he was leader when 
solidarity was banned 
</TEXT>
