<TEXT>
the sinking of a nuclearpowered submarine off the 
coast of norway is at least the third serious incident in the 
soviet nuclear fleet in 2 years and comes amid growing soviet 
public concern over nuclear safety 
the accident came five months after a reported nearmeltdown in 
a nuclear reactor aboard a soviet icebreaker in the port city of 
murmansk 
that accident touched off a public outcry that prevented another 
nuclearpowered ship from docking in the far east 
in october 1986 three sailors died in a fire and explosion 
aboard a yankeeclass nuclearpowered submarine in the atlantic 
ocean that was armed with ballistic missiles 
since the april 26 1986 explosion and fire at the chernobyl 
nuclear power plant in the ukraine that killed at least 31 people 
and sent a cloud of radiation into the atmosphere soviet people 
have become wary of nuclear power both on land and at sea 
in november the nuclear powered icebreaker rossiya pulled into 
murmansk near the border with finland for the routine changing of 
a filter in one of its two pressurized reactors 
a report in the newspaper vodny transport four months after the 
incident said the routine job almost turned into a disastrous 
nuclear meltdown 
according to the report the chief physicist aboard the ship 
gave incorrect instructions to a reactor operator who in turn 
drained vital cooling water from operating reactor rather than the 
one shut down for the repairs 
had the water drained 30 minutes longer a meltdown releasing 
radiation into the air over the city of 440000 people would have 
occurred the newspaper said the situation was liquidated in 
four minutes the newspapers murmansk correspondent said 
three days later the newspaper sovietskaya rossiya said two 
cities and a region in the soviet far east refused entry to a 
nuclearpowered merchant ship sevmorput which had reported 
fractures in its hull 
a deficit of information piled on top of the invisible shadow 
of the chernobyl tragedy and the most complex ecological situation 
in the region detonated a powerful explosion of public 
indignation the newspaper said 
officials claimed that the hull fractures presented no danger to 
the nuclear plant on the ship but the public was not assured at 
last report the ship was still anchored off vladivostok its fate 
undecided 
refusal of officials in the ports of vladivostok and nakhodka 
and the region of magadan highlighted a groundswell of public 
opposition to nuclear power that began with the chernobyl disaster 
the policy of glasnost or openness initiated by president 
mikhail s gorbachev has resulted in a growing vocal opposition to 
nuclear power 
officials scrapped plans to build six nuclear power stations 
because of safety concerns another plant in armenia was closed 
after the dec 7 earthquake that killed 25000 people prompted 
fears of a nuclear disaster 
although the sinking of a nuclear submarine off the coast of 
norway did not affect public safety in the soviet union it 
reinforced concerns about the safety of nuclear power 
with those concerns in mind officials have apparently changed 
the course of the countrys ambitious nuclear program 
previously nuclear stations were concentrated in populous 
regions in the eastern part of the country hydroelectric plants 
now will be built to supply local power and nuclear stations will 
be constructed in remote regions where they will pose little danger 
to the public 
