distorts the ethics process that i hope that respectable and 
responsible democrats will intervene 
the deal involved 21 investors who put 5000 each into a 
partnership formed to promote the book in return for their 
investment the partners were promised half the publishers 
profits but the publisher ended up losing money on the book and 
the investors got a tax writeoff 
gingrichs wife marianne gingrich who coauthored the book 
has said she received less than 10000 of the 105000 raised by 
the partnership for arranging the deal and coordinating the 
promotional effort she also received a 26 tax benefit from her 
share of the partnership 
mrs gingrich said last month that the ethics committee had been 
consulted before the partnership contracts were signed to ensure 
that the arrangement did not violate any house rules 
alexander contends in the complaint that the promotional deal 
may have violated house rules limiting outside earned income and 
gifts that a member can receive he said the deal also may have 
violated house rules governing the use of campaign funds and 
government resources and requiring disclosure of travel 
reimbursements 
