<TEXT>
a former city attorney was sentenced 
friday to 90 days in jail and four excommissioners got two years 
probation on convictions for guaranteeing themselves jobs in 
settling a federal votingrights lawsuit 
in addition to the jail sentence attorney wendell wright was 
fined 5000 said vermilion county states attorney craig 
dearmond he was the prime mover in the conspiracy he said 
the guy who orchestrated the whole thing 
former commissioners wilbur scharlau ernie cox jerome brown 
and raymond randall each were sentenced to two years unsupervised 
probation fined 1000 each and forfeited their pension rights and 
jobs with the city 
the sentences were handed down by circuit judge paul komada but 
the penalties were stayed and the defendants released on bond 
pending appeal of the case dearmond said 
the men were convicted in february of conflict of interest 
conspiracy and violation of a municipal code that bars entering 
into a contract for personal gain all but wright also were 
convicted of official misconduct 
the case stems from a 1987 lawsuit filed under the federal 
voting rights act the parties reached a settlement that guaranteed 
the commissioners city jobs for three years after the city adopted 
a new form of government 
the lawsuit alleged that danvilles longtime mayorcommissioner 
form of government discriminated against blacks the city held 
atlarge elections of the commissioners who headed city departments 
and formed the city council 
under the settlement council members represent newly outlined 
city wards 
aldermanic elections were held in december 1987 and two blacks 
were among those elected the first blacks to serve on the council 
since the old system was adopted 60 years earlier 
the settlement also specified that scharlau cox randall and 
brown would have jobs as department heads for three years in the 
new system 
